9 COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to S.P. 360, L.D. 795, “An Act to Exempt
10 Pegmatite Mining from the Maine Metallic Mineral Mining Act and Establish a Permit-by-
11 rule Process”
12 Amend the bill by striking out the title and substituting the following:
13 'An Act to Establish a Waiver Process from the Permit Requirements for the Use of
14 Explosives in Recreational or Hobby Mining Activities'
15 Amend the bill by striking out everything after the enacting clause and inserting the
16 following:
17 'Sec. 1. 25 MRSA §2473-A is enacted to read:
18 §2473-A. Waiver of permit requirements for recreational or hobby mining
19 Notwithstanding section 2473, a person intending to conduct recreational or hobby
20 mining activities may request and the commissioner may approve a waiver from the permit
21 requirements of section 2473 for the possession, use, storage and transportation of
22 explosives for use in the recreational or hobby mining activities.
23 1. Criteria for approval. The commissioner may approve a waiver under this section
24 if the commissioner determines that:
25 A. The person requesting the waiver has not committed any violations of this chapter
26 or the rules adopted pursuant to this chapter or any other violations of law or rules
27 relating to public safety;
28 B. The person requesting the waiver has demonstrated to the commissioner's
29 satisfaction that compliance with the requirements of this chapter is impractical with
30 respect to the recreational or hobby mining activities the person intends to conduct;
31 C. Approving the waiver will not compromise public safety or pose a risk to public or
32 private property;
Page 1 - 132LR1704(02)
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT

COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to S.P. 360, L.D. 795
1 D. The person requesting the waiver has agreed to implement alternative safety
2 measures for the possession, use, storage and transportation of explosives as directed
3 by the commissioner; and
4 E. The person requesting the waiver had previously been issued a waiver from the
5 requirements of section 2473 by the commissioner prior to March 4, 2025.
6 2. Rules. The commissioner may adopt rules as necessary to implement this section.
7 Rules adopted pursuant to this subsection are routine technical rules as defined in Title 5,
8 chapter 375, subchapter 2-A.
9 As used in this section, "recreational or hobby mining activities" means mining
10 activities for which a person is not required to obtain a permit under the Maine Metallic
11 Mineral Mining Act and that are conducted for a noncommercial purpose.'
12 Amend the bill by relettering or renumbering any nonconsecutive Part letter or section
13 number to read consecutively.
14 SUMMARY
1155 This amendment changes the title of and replaces the bill. It amends the laws regulating
1166 explosives and flammable liquids to provide that the Commissioner of Public Safety may
1177 approve a waiver from the requirement that a person possessing, using, storing or
1188 transporting explosives obtain a permit from the commissioner if the person is intending to
1199 conduct recreational or hobby mining activities and satisfies other specified criteria,
2200 including a requirement that the person requesting the waiver had previously been issued a
2211 waiver from the permit requirements prior to March 4, 2025. The amendment defines
2222 "recreational or hobby mining activities" as mining activities that are not required to obtain
2233 a permit under the Maine Metallic Mineral Mining Act and that are conducted for a
2244 noncommercial purpose.
